<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

    <!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
        <handout margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="Week9Wed">
            <title>Wednesday Week 9 - Using Trigonometric Identities</title>
<page>
        <objectives>
          <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Use trigonometric identities to solve trigonometric equations
                </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </objectives>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    In this class we have solved trigonometric equations on specified domains. Now we will solve more complicated equations using trigonometric identities as a simplification strategy.
                </p>
            </introduction>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Strategy for Solving Trigonometric Equations</title>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                See if you can use a trigonometric identity to replace some part of the equation to make a simpler equation.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Do algebra to reduce the equation to one or more of the form
                <md>
                    \text{trigonometric function} = \text{number}.
                </md>
                This may use strategies from other families, such as factoring.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Use inverse functions to obtain <em>some</em> solutions. Then use graphs and/or the unit circle to find additional solutions.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</paragraphs>

<example>
    <statement>
    <p workspace="3in">
    Solve
    <md>
        \sin(2x) = \sin(x)
    </md>
    on the interval <m>0\leq x\leq 2\pi</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
</example>

</page>
<page>

<p>
    Let's do another example to illustrate a neat simplification trick.
</p>



<example>
    <statement>
        <p workspace="4in">
            Solve the equation
            <md>
                2\sin^2(\theta)  = 3\cos(\theta) + 3
            </md>
            with <m>0\leq \theta \leq 2\pi</m>.
        Tricks:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Use the Pythagorean Identity to turn this into an equation that only involves cosine.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Replace <m>\cos(\theta)</m> with the variable <m>c</m> to make the algebra look easier.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        </p>
        
    </statement>

</example>

</page>
<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Problems</title>
<p>
    
</p>
<ol>
    <li>
        <p workspace="3in">
           Use the double-angle identity for sine and <m>\sin\left(t+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)  = \cos(t)</m> to solve
           <md>
            \sin(2t) = \sqrt{3}\sin\left(t+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)
           </md>
           with <m>0\leq t\leq 2\pi</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace="3.5in">
            Solve the equation
            <md>
                \tan(2t) + \tan(t) = 0
            </md>
            with <m>0\leq t\leq 2\pi</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>

</paragraphs>   



</page>

        

</handout>
